00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:27.090
But George is here.

00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:30.660
So if you've got
questions, you can ask me.

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:32.720
I don't mind being
interrupted at any time.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.917
But also, if you want
George to answer something,

00:00:36.917 --> 00:00:38.000
he's sitting here as well.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.450
So he can also contribute.

00:00:41.450 --> 00:00:47.090
So last time, George was looking
at the Fourier transforming

00:00:47.090 --> 00:00:49.330
property of a lens.

00:00:49.330 --> 00:00:55.070
And he looks at the--
derived the 1D case, where

00:00:55.070 --> 00:00:59.270
you've just got a function of, x
rather than a function of x, y.

00:00:59.270 --> 00:01:03.470
You've got this
transparency a distance z

00:01:03.470 --> 00:01:06.100
in front of the lens.

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:09.990
And then you've got a
screen placed a distance

00:01:09.990 --> 00:01:12.650
f behind the lens.

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:16.150
And so the question is, what
do you get on that screen?

00:01:16.150 --> 00:01:20.590
And I'm not going to go
through all the algebra of that

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:22.780
again because George
did it last time.

00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:23.950
This was the calculus.

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:25.390
This was the answer.

00:01:25.390 --> 00:01:31.660
What you find is that what
you get in this plane here

00:01:31.660 --> 00:01:35.050
is actually the
Fourier transform

00:01:35.050 --> 00:01:39.330
of the thin transparency.

00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:43.060
So g of x is this
transparency here.

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:46.320
You get the Fourier
transformer that.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:51.970
And multiplied by
a parabolic phase

00:01:51.970 --> 00:01:56.710
factor, which depends on the
position of this screen--

00:01:56.710 --> 00:01:59.980
of the transparency.

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:02.200
What is the value of this z?

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:08.620
You'll notice that you get this
factor here, 1 minus z over f.

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:12.430
So if z equals f,
this is going to be 0.

00:02:12.430 --> 00:02:15.110
And this phase factor
is going to disappear.

00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:18.170
So for the special
case where z equals

00:02:18.170 --> 00:02:23.390
f, all you see here is just
the Fourier transform of this.

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:26.580
Very simple-- very
simple answer.

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:30.550
And people actually have known
this for quite a long time.

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:32.900
And at one time, it did
look really attractive

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:35.600
that you could
actually imagine using

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:39.620
this as a real way of
doing Fourier transforms.

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:42.910
Especially as we're
now going to do,

00:02:42.910 --> 00:02:48.230
you can immediately generalize
that to the 2D case.

00:02:48.230 --> 00:02:52.040
So you can do a 2D
Fourier transform.

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:56.810
And when you think that the
light propagates through this

00:02:56.810 --> 00:02:59.750
at the speed of light, you
can do a 2D Fourier transform

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:01.610
at the speed of light.

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:03.530
And when people
first realized this,

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:05.765
which was back in the 1950s--

00:03:05.765 --> 00:03:11.540
'50s or early '60s, computers
were very slow then.

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:16.020
So doing a 2D Fourier
transform was not trivial.

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:19.760
So a lot of effort was put into
trying to design instruments

00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:20.270
to do that.

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:20.820
Yes.

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:22.190
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Do you
know who was the first one

00:03:22.190 --> 00:03:22.857
to realize this?

00:03:22.857 --> 00:03:25.263
Was it Vander Lugt?

00:03:25.263 --> 00:03:26.930
COLIN SHEPPARD: The
question is, who was

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:29.960
the first to recognize that?

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:36.845
Yeah Vander Lugt was
at Michigan, wasn't he?

00:03:36.845 --> 00:03:40.580
And interestingly,
the holography guys

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:42.733
were also in the same lab.

00:03:42.733 --> 00:03:43.650
What's the guy's name.

00:03:43.650 --> 00:03:45.790
The one-- Emmett Leith.

00:03:45.790 --> 00:03:50.240
And interestingly, Emmett
Leith and Vander Lugt

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:54.920
both published virtually the
same paper in the same year.

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:58.295
It's a very, very interesting
historical thing there.

00:03:58.295 --> 00:04:00.170
They're both from the
same lab, and they both

00:04:00.170 --> 00:04:04.100
invented almost the same
idea as far as I can see.

00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:07.670
And neither of them
referred to the other guy.

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:09.500
Very peculiar.

00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:13.030
Anyway, I don't know who really
came up with this idea first.

00:04:13.030 --> 00:04:21.440
But actually, I suspect that
actually, even Ernst Abbe

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:23.970
realized this.

00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:30.320
Ernst Abbe was the scientist who
designed the Zeiss microscopes

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:34.530
120, 130 years ago.

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:38.180
And he came up with a
theory for image formation

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:39.940
in a microscope,
which is actually

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:41.690
what we're going to
be getting onto pretty

00:04:41.690 --> 00:04:43.250
well, the next thing--

00:04:43.250 --> 00:04:46.940
the imaging with a 4F F system.

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:50.130
He understood that
130 years ago.

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:52.940
And I don't think he's often
given as much credit is

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:54.180
he should get.

00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:56.600
Anyway, you can
use this as a way

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:00.130
of doing a Fourier transform,
and even a 2D Fourier

00:05:00.130 --> 00:05:00.860
transform.

00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:02.780
So you see, going
from this stage

00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:06.000
to this stage is
trivial, really.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.500
All we've done here
is assuming that it's

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:13.400
a separable function
of x and y so you

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:16.700
get exactly the same
sort of integral for y

00:05:16.700 --> 00:05:18.860
as you get for x.

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:21.920
So it now becomes
a double integral.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:25.430
This is the two-dimensional
Fourier transform object

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:28.200
of g of x, y.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:34.460
And you can see, you get
again the phase factor.

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:37.100
Here, because it's
separable, you've

00:05:37.100 --> 00:05:40.310
got this e to the
i pi x squared,

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:43.170
and you got an e to
the i pi y squared.

00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:46.700
And of course, x squared
plus y squared very nicely

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:48.390
equals r squared.

00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:54.920
So this becomes a
spherical type wave.

00:05:54.920 --> 00:06:00.760
So we've still got this 1 minus
z over f So if z equals f,

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:04.750
then again, this
phase factor vanishes,

00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:09.410
and we end up with just
the pure Fourier transform.

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:11.100
Yeah, as I say,
so a lot of people

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:14.100
thought that this
was quite a neat way

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:16.200
of doing Fourier transforms.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:19.590
There was a lot of work
on optical computers

00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:23.280
all the way through
the '60s and '70s.

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:26.700
But the trouble is that, as
fast as they could develop

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:30.810
these systems, the
computer people developed

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:32.800
their computers even faster.

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:36.040
So they were always one
step behind, I think.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:37.740
So I think in the
end, people realized

00:06:37.740 --> 00:06:41.880
it was a waste of time,
and that it was never

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:49.850
really going to become
a practical way of doing

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:51.300
real calculations.

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:52.970
But in the early days, it was.

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:55.850
And Emmett Leith we
were just mentioning,

00:06:55.850 --> 00:06:59.420
he first developed these
systems for actually

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:07.730
analyzing the images they
took from a synthetic aperture

00:07:07.730 --> 00:07:14.360
They'd fly an aeroplane over
North Korea, taking pictures.

00:07:14.360 --> 00:07:19.370
And then the idea was that
the plane takes many pictures

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:23.960
as it's traveling along, and
they're coherent with respect

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:24.600
to each other.

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:29.880
So you can actually combine
them digitally afterwards

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:33.380
and get an image, which
has got amazing resolution.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:36.770
And you can see the guy in North
Korea reading his newspaper

00:07:36.770 --> 00:07:39.260
or whatever.

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:42.860
So they really did that
sort of thing way back then.

00:07:42.860 --> 00:07:46.700
Right, so that's the
equation here then.

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:50.120
And yeah, so this is
just going through how

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:52.340
that thing was derived.

00:07:52.340 --> 00:08:00.300
So we've got the screen
here, the g of x.

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:03.990
By the time we get
here, it's convolved

00:08:03.990 --> 00:08:07.930
with some parabolic
phase function.

00:08:07.930 --> 00:08:09.630
And then after it
goes through here,

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:13.110
it's multiplied by another
parabolic phase function.

00:08:13.110 --> 00:08:15.830
And then as it
propagates here, it's

00:08:15.830 --> 00:08:19.330
convolved with another
parabolic phase function.

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:24.050
And if we have that magic
condition, that this is f

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:28.080
and this is f, most of these
parabolic phases cancel out

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:31.300
and we're left with this
very simple final answer.

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:33.090
So that's basically
what's happening.

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:37.260
And George went through the
various stages of doing this.

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:41.429
Of course, you end up with a
couple of integrals of products

00:08:41.429 --> 00:08:43.100
of three phase functions here.

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:49.350
So the algebra process
was quite complicated.

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:53.270
Well, not really complicated,
but just lengthy.

00:08:53.270 --> 00:08:56.720
But everything in
the end cancels.

00:08:56.720 --> 00:09:00.240
If you haven't got z
equals 2f, though, then you

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:05.400
can see that you have
got this phase factor.

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:08.960
So you don't actually get
exactly the Fourier transform

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:10.780
in this plane in that case.

00:09:10.780 --> 00:09:13.290
You get the Fourier
transform multiplied

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:15.630
by this phase factor.

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:18.890
And that can be
important in some cases.

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:22.750
That's something that you
need to take into account.

00:09:22.750 --> 00:09:26.490
There's another
special case, actually.

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:29.620
That's the case when z equals 0.

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:33.500
The case when z equals
0 is if this screen

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:35.030
coincides with the lens--

00:09:35.030 --> 00:09:37.656
immediately close
up to the lens.

00:09:37.656 --> 00:09:41.060
And I think Goodman does
that one as well, doesn't he.

00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:45.130
And so if z equals 0, this goes.

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:47.330
And so we're still left
with this phase factor,

00:09:47.330 --> 00:09:52.797
e to the i pi x double
dash squared over lambda f.

00:09:52.797 --> 00:09:54.380
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
And also, Goodman

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:56.570
does the case of
the transparency

00:09:56.570 --> 00:09:59.247
after the lens, which I
did not do in the notes.

00:09:59.247 --> 00:10:00.330
COLIN SHEPPARD: Right, OK.

00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:04.320
Yeah, so Goodman does this
case of the transparency placed

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:04.820
in here.

00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:06.695
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That this is z negative.

00:10:06.695 --> 00:10:11.015
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah, but
it's very similar answers.

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:22.510
OK, so this is just
writing down finally, then.

00:10:22.510 --> 00:10:29.650
We're defining then the Fourier
transform of little g is big G.

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:33.220
So the final answer is that
you've got this parabolic phase

00:10:33.220 --> 00:10:37.210
function times the
Fourier transform of g.

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:48.380
OK.

00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:55.030
So this is pointing
out that we've now

00:10:55.030 --> 00:10:58.960
looked at two different ways
you can do a Fourier transform.

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:04.030
One way is to just propagate
the light a very large distance.

00:11:04.030 --> 00:11:07.060
You remember, if you have
[? frame ?] of a diffraction,

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:13.600
if your screen is a very long
way away from the diffracting

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:16.960
screen, object,
whatever it was called--

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:20.410
transparency then again,
you get this Fourier

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:22.120
transform relationship.

00:11:22.120 --> 00:11:25.660
But of course, here he's
put a proportional side.

00:11:25.660 --> 00:11:28.150
There's some things
out the front there.

00:11:28.150 --> 00:11:31.930
And in particular, there's going
to be, again, a parabolic phase

00:11:31.930 --> 00:11:33.070
term, isn't there?

00:11:33.070 --> 00:11:37.180
Because in this case here,
what you'd expect actually

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:38.950
is that this
Fourier transform is

00:11:38.950 --> 00:11:43.840
going to be actually on the
surface of some curved surface,

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:46.870
not of a plane surface.

00:11:46.870 --> 00:11:50.800
So if the screen
is plane, then it's

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:55.960
going to be multiplied by
some parabolic phase term.

00:11:55.960 --> 00:11:59.200
And now we've just looked
at this other case where

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:03.280
we don't have to have a
very large lab in order

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:05.560
to do this experiment.

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:08.020
We can actually make the
experiment quite small

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:12.100
so that it fits on top of the
table just by using a lens.

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:16.420
And really what you can see,
that that is actually doing,

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:19.630
according to your
geometrical optics ideas now,

00:12:19.630 --> 00:12:22.390
you can see what this is doing.

00:12:22.390 --> 00:12:27.680
This is producing an
image of this at infinity.

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:30.800
So you can see that these two
things are actually equivalent.

00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:33.550
Well, what it's
doing is bringing

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:38.680
what would have been at
infinity to some finite plane.

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:42.190
So that's all it's doing there.

00:12:42.190 --> 00:12:45.070
But again, we've got
this [? string ?]

00:12:45.070 --> 00:12:49.580
here, this proportional
sign, which

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:53.340
means there's some other
constant factors out there,

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:58.940
including in general this
parabolic phase factor, which

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:06.150
for this particular case, when
you got f and f, it disappears.

00:13:06.150 --> 00:13:09.390
The parabolic phase
function disappears

00:13:09.390 --> 00:13:13.830
when you've got this very, very
special case with the two f's

00:13:13.830 --> 00:13:14.330
there.

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:21.720
OK, now this one.

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:23.640
What this is really
trying to show

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:25.335
is that, really,
there's two ways

00:13:25.335 --> 00:13:26.460
of looking at this problem.

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:32.460
These two diagrams
here are really

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:37.950
trying to show the
same case, but trying

00:13:37.950 --> 00:13:42.360
to get you thinking about
a different way of viewing

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:43.450
the problem.

00:13:43.450 --> 00:13:46.500
So in this case
here, you can think

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:55.180
of any point on the
screen on the transparency

00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:58.440
is going to act
like a point source.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.430
So it's going to produce a
spherical expanding wave.

00:14:02.430 --> 00:14:06.270
And then this is a distance
f, so that spherical wave

00:14:06.270 --> 00:14:07.950
is going to be
converted into a plane

00:14:07.950 --> 00:14:12.240
wave The angle of propagation
of this plane wave

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:15.960
depends on the distance at
this point from the origin,

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:17.880
of course.

00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:22.440
And so you can think, then,
of what you see on the screen

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:27.360
as being made up of
what's called an angular

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:31.500
spectrum of plane waves, where
the strength of each of those

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:35.940
and get a spectrum components
comes about from the value

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:39.410
of at that point.

00:14:39.410 --> 00:14:42.680
So that's one way of
thinking about it.

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:44.640
And this way [INAUDIBLE]
thinking about it

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:45.600
the other way.

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:48.550
This way, you're
thinking of the object.

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:50.070
It's going to diffract.

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:55.230
If you imagine your transparency
as being like a grating,

00:14:55.230 --> 00:14:57.985
it produces a diffraction.

00:14:57.985 --> 00:15:01.230
It's producing
light grating orders

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:04.830
For example, if this
was a very simple case

00:15:04.830 --> 00:15:08.460
of a sinusoidal
grating, you'd expect it

00:15:08.460 --> 00:15:11.100
to produce some grating orders.

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:15.840
And these grating orders
correspond to plane waves

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.000
traveling in particular angles.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.240
So this shows the
angular spectrum

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:29.040
of the diffraction of the light
given by the transparency.

00:15:29.040 --> 00:15:35.040
And then the lens collects
these different plane

00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:36.750
white components.

00:15:36.750 --> 00:15:39.300
All of them are
going to be converted

00:15:39.300 --> 00:15:42.750
into a spherical
converging wave that

00:15:42.750 --> 00:15:45.420
converges a distance f away.

00:15:45.420 --> 00:15:49.440
It doesn't say that, but
this must be [? there. ?]

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:55.360
And the plane wave's
moving at different angles

00:15:55.360 --> 00:16:00.240
are going to converge to a
point which, of course, is

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:05.970
proportional to the sine of
the angle of the propagation.

