the geometry showing
the inversion,

00:31:42.180 --> 00:31:47.180
the point above the axis has
come to an image below the axis

00:31:47.180 --> 00:31:48.220
here.

00:31:48.220 --> 00:31:51.560
So that's the one way
of thinking about it.

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:54.290
And then the other way
is to think in terms

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.300
of spatial frequencies.

00:31:56.300 --> 00:32:00.230
We think of this object as
being like a grating, which

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:02.270
is going to produce
grating orders which

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:04.550
travel in different directions.

00:32:04.550 --> 00:32:09.660
Each of these grating
orders is like a plane wave.

00:32:09.660 --> 00:32:11.570
And when it reaches
the lens, it's

00:32:11.570 --> 00:32:16.820
going to produce a converging
spherical wave, which

00:32:16.820 --> 00:32:22.530
comes to a focus at
distance f behind the lens.

00:32:22.530 --> 00:32:24.550
And then after that, of
course, it doesn't stop.

00:32:24.550 --> 00:32:25.830
But it carries on.

00:32:25.830 --> 00:32:29.970
It diverges again,
reaches the second lens.

00:32:29.970 --> 00:32:32.100
And then the second
lens, because this

00:32:32.100 --> 00:32:35.730
is a spherical wave coming
from a distance f away,

00:32:35.730 --> 00:32:38.450
is converted into
a plane wave again.

00:32:38.450 --> 00:32:44.790
So again, you've got this nice
symmetry between what goes in

00:32:44.790 --> 00:32:46.950
and what comes out.

00:32:46.950 --> 00:32:50.930
So there are these
really different ways

00:32:50.930 --> 00:32:53.510
of thinking about how
this is all going on.

