Lots of interesting
things coming up later.

00:33:49.590 --> 00:33:52.780
OK, so we're going to
carry on straight away

00:33:52.780 --> 00:33:56.350
with more of this 4F system
and spatial filtering.

00:33:56.350 --> 00:33:59.750
So we're just getting
started on this.

00:33:59.750 --> 00:34:01.960
And so there's lots of
very interesting things

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:03.760
you can do with these.

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:06.490
So this is back to the same
thing again [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:09.730
showing again, but a
bit more detail now,

00:34:09.730 --> 00:34:13.030
because we're actually
going to really look

00:34:13.030 --> 00:34:16.600
at more detail of where
these orders are formed

00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:18.739
and what you can do with them.

00:34:18.739 --> 00:34:24.090
So we have a grating object.

00:34:24.090 --> 00:34:27.540
Let's imagine this is just
a 1 plus a cosine, which

00:34:27.540 --> 00:34:30.270
means then it
produces a zero order,

00:34:30.270 --> 00:34:33.120
and then a plus
and minus 1 order.

00:34:33.120 --> 00:34:35.080
So three plane waves.

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:37.320
And as we said, each
of those plane waves

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:43.050
is going to be converted to
a converging spherical wave.

00:34:43.050 --> 00:34:46.199
And so in this back
focal plane, you'll

00:34:46.199 --> 00:34:51.310
see three spots corresponding
to the three orders.

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:55.760
And then carrying
on, these plane waves

00:34:55.760 --> 00:34:58.610
then converted back
into a spherical wave.

00:34:58.610 --> 00:35:02.120
And you get an image which
is back to the grating again.

00:35:02.120 --> 00:35:06.410
So at the moment,
the optical system

00:35:06.410 --> 00:35:08.990
has transmitted all
the information.

00:35:08.990 --> 00:35:12.740
And so what we really
expect is that the image

00:35:12.740 --> 00:35:16.190
is exactly the same as the
object, apart from the fact

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:21.020
it's inverted and it might be
magnified, or the opposite.

00:35:21.020 --> 00:35:24.870
But the resolution you'd
expect would be the same.

00:35:24.870 --> 00:35:29.520
All the detail in here,
you'd expect to see in there.

00:35:29.520 --> 00:35:32.870
So the next thing
to look at is what

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:35.600
happens if we now
place something

00:35:35.600 --> 00:35:39.260
in this plane that changes
the relative strength

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:41.060
of these different orders.

00:35:41.060 --> 00:35:43.640
And there are lots of
things that we could try.

00:35:43.640 --> 00:35:47.030
The first one, the
simplest one to look at,

00:35:47.030 --> 00:35:51.140
is what happens if we just
put in something, a mask

00:35:51.140 --> 00:35:58.160
here that lets through the
zero order and not the others.

00:35:58.160 --> 00:36:03.560
The plus 1 and the minus 1 order
are obstructed by this screen.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:07.490
So all we let through
is this single order,

00:36:07.490 --> 00:36:11.520
which is going to be
converted to a plane wave.

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:15.990
And so on your screen here, all
you'll see is the plane wave.

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:18.510
So the image that you see--

00:36:18.510 --> 00:36:19.680
well, I call it an image.

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:21.810
But it's not really
much of an image.

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:24.420
It's completely featureless.

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:29.340
It's just like a gray spot--

00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:30.900
a gray region.

00:36:30.900 --> 00:36:32.500
There's no detail there.

00:36:32.500 --> 00:36:37.230
So we've lost that structure.

00:36:37.230 --> 00:36:41.280
Actually, because we
put this mask in here,

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:46.740
the structure is beyond
the resolution limit

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:48.640
of the optical system.

00:36:48.640 --> 00:36:49.770
And so we can't see it.

00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:58.840
OK, so this is what we might
call a low-pass filter.

00:36:58.840 --> 00:37:02.610
So if you think of these
as being like these grating

00:37:02.610 --> 00:37:06.420
orders basically represent
different spatial frequencies.

00:37:06.420 --> 00:37:11.370
So just in analogy with what
you have in electricity,

00:37:11.370 --> 00:37:14.220
where you've got
frequencies and time,

00:37:14.220 --> 00:37:20.290
in space, we've got distance and
we've got spatial frequencies.

00:37:20.290 --> 00:37:25.120
So this is why we could talk
about low-pass filtering.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:27.530
We're filtering the
spatial frequencies.

00:37:27.530 --> 00:37:31.440
And just like in
time, you remember

00:37:31.440 --> 00:37:34.800
when you've got
your hi-fi system,

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:38.070
if you turn down
the treble, that's

00:37:38.070 --> 00:37:41.160
acting like a low-pass filter.

00:37:41.160 --> 00:37:44.880
It's cutting out the
high-frequency sound

00:37:44.880 --> 00:37:47.850
and letting through the
low-frequency sound only,

00:37:47.850 --> 00:37:48.690
isn't it?

00:37:48.690 --> 00:37:51.340
So that's what we call
a low-pass filter.

00:37:51.340 --> 00:37:53.680
And this is exactly the same.

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:55.140
We've put in the mask.

00:37:55.140 --> 00:37:59.280
It's a bit different in a
way from the electronic case,

00:37:59.280 --> 00:38:01.560
because in optics, we've
got a lot more freedom

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:03.240
as to what we can do.

00:38:03.240 --> 00:38:05.550
We can actually put in
something here which

00:38:05.550 --> 00:38:08.220
has got real sharp edges to it.

00:38:08.220 --> 00:38:12.170
In electronics, if you're
trying to make a filter,

00:38:12.170 --> 00:38:15.240
there's always a
limit to how much

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:18.730
you can make the roll
off of the filter.

00:38:18.730 --> 00:38:20.940
So you can't get something
that suddenly cuts off

00:38:20.940 --> 00:38:21.980
like that very easily.

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:31.030
OK, so this is going
through the maths of this.

00:38:31.030 --> 00:38:36.610
Our original transparency,
then, is a 1 plus cosine.

00:38:36.610 --> 00:38:40.600
And the 1 plus cosine,
we Fourier transform

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:44.750
that to find what we
call the object spectrum.

00:38:44.750 --> 00:38:50.080
And so in this case, finding
the Fourier transform of cosine

00:38:50.080 --> 00:38:52.690
is very straightforward,
because we just

00:38:52.690 --> 00:38:56.860
expand cosine as e to
the i something plus e

00:38:56.860 --> 00:38:59.730
on the minus i something over 2.

00:38:59.730 --> 00:39:04.360
And each of those e
to the i type terms

00:39:04.360 --> 00:39:09.670
will correspond to
a single frequency.

00:39:09.670 --> 00:39:13.660
So we end up now with three
terms at different frequencies.

00:39:13.660 --> 00:39:18.670
The one Fourier transforms to
a delta function of u, which

00:39:18.670 --> 00:39:22.180
is a spike where u equals 0.

00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:25.030
And the two components
of the cosine

00:39:25.030 --> 00:39:32.350
correspond to another 2 delta
functions, each situated--

00:39:32.350 --> 00:39:36.210
this one's a u
equals some value u0.

00:39:36.210 --> 00:39:40.150
And this one is some
value u equals minus u0.

00:39:40.150 --> 00:39:44.320
So you've got these three spikes
that we've been talking about

00:39:44.320 --> 00:39:46.750
for the last few slides now.

00:39:46.750 --> 00:39:51.790
So this is the object spectrum.

00:39:51.790 --> 00:39:55.340
It's the angular spectrum
that we've got here.

00:39:55.340 --> 00:39:59.590
So actually, you can see that
u here basically represents

00:39:59.590 --> 00:40:04.263
the angle that these plane
waves are traveling in.

00:40:04.263 --> 00:40:05.680
And there's three
different angles

00:40:05.680 --> 00:40:09.630
that the light can travel in.

00:40:09.630 --> 00:40:16.660
And so yeah, that
will propagate, then.

00:40:16.660 --> 00:40:19.360
And as we've said
before, you can

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:24.320
see that these rays
are moving at an angle.

00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:29.980
And so as you go
along a distance f,

00:40:29.980 --> 00:40:32.770
you get a shift
in the x position

00:40:32.770 --> 00:40:37.230
which is given by, of
course, the slope of this.

00:40:37.230 --> 00:40:41.170
The more the slope, the
more it deflects by the time

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:43.150
you travel a distance f.

00:40:43.150 --> 00:40:47.150
So this then gives the
shifts of these two things.

00:40:47.150 --> 00:40:51.700
So that's before
the screen, then--

00:40:51.700 --> 00:40:53.350
sorry, before the mask.

00:41:01.820 --> 00:41:04.324
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:41:39.030 --> 00:41:41.110
Yeah, so this is showing, then--

00:41:41.110 --> 00:41:46.250
so these raise, then,
as they come down here.

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:48.190
We put in this
pupil mask which is

00:41:48.190 --> 00:41:49.990
going to get rid of these two.

00:41:49.990 --> 00:41:51.520
And it just leaves
the other one.

00:41:51.520 --> 00:41:55.660
So we just left them
with our single beam,

00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:59.350
which as we said before gives
an image which is not really

00:41:59.350 --> 00:41:59.850
an image.

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:05.500
Right, yeah, so
after the pupil mask,

00:42:05.500 --> 00:42:06.990
we multiplied by the mask.

00:42:06.990 --> 00:42:08.080
Gets rid of those two.

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:10.090
Just leaves the other one.

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:14.920
And finally, then, the
final image you'll see

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:17.860
is going to be the Fourier
transformer of that.

00:42:17.860 --> 00:42:22.400
And the Fourier transform of the
delta function is a constant.

00:42:22.400 --> 00:42:26.530
And so you see something
which has got no detail in it.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:35.250
OK, so this gives
another example, then.

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:41.970
Here, we're looking at some
binary amplitude grating.

00:42:41.970 --> 00:42:44.820
So this is a
particular example--

00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:46.060
another example.

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.810
So last time, we looked
at the cosine type thing.

00:42:48.810 --> 00:42:51.010
So this one is now
a binary grating,

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:53.250
which means that the
object is something

00:42:53.250 --> 00:42:56.080
which is either black or white.

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:57.790
And we shine a light onto this.

00:42:57.790 --> 00:43:01.420
So it's like a
square wave grating.

00:43:01.420 --> 00:43:06.010
And so unlike the previous
case where cosine, of course,

00:43:06.010 --> 00:43:10.690
just produced those
three grating components,

00:43:10.690 --> 00:43:14.380
in this case, there's going
to be a whole load of grating

00:43:14.380 --> 00:43:15.040
components.

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:17.380
They're going to go on forever.

00:43:17.380 --> 00:43:19.600
But they get weaker and weaker.

00:43:19.600 --> 00:43:23.050
And so you can see here,
it shows a few of them.

00:43:23.050 --> 00:43:25.180
The first, the
second, so there'll

00:43:25.180 --> 00:43:27.230
be the third, the
fourth, and so on.

00:43:27.230 --> 00:43:29.490
And then minus 1,
and so on and so on.

00:43:29.490 --> 00:43:33.340
And each of these is moving
at a different angle.

00:43:33.340 --> 00:43:37.960
So when the plane wave
gets to the pupil mask--

00:43:37.960 --> 00:43:44.040
sorry, when the plane wave
is focused to the pupil mask,

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:45.880
it's going to reach there.

00:43:45.880 --> 00:43:49.360
At a point, the distance
from the axis, of course,

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:55.000
is going to depend on the angle
of this plane wave component,

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:56.890
the grating component.

00:43:56.890 --> 00:43:59.440
So if you look
here, you're going

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:02.710
to see all these different
grating orders all

00:44:02.710 --> 00:44:05.420
arrayed in this position here.

00:44:05.420 --> 00:44:12.310
And so by putting some
sort of mask here,

00:44:12.310 --> 00:44:17.650
we can monitor and change the
relative strength or phrase

00:44:17.650 --> 00:44:21.100
or whatever we like of
those different components.

00:44:21.100 --> 00:44:23.410
And then they'll
be added together,

00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:28.040
produce some nice effect that
we might want to look at.

00:44:28.040 --> 00:44:31.880
So let's see what we're
going to get in this case.

00:44:31.880 --> 00:44:34.660
So in this particular
case in the picture,

00:44:34.660 --> 00:44:37.570
the size of this
aperture is enough to let

00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:41.950
through the central three
components, the zero order

00:44:41.950 --> 00:44:44.860
and the plus and minus 1 order.

00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:48.430
But it stopped all
the other ones.

00:44:48.430 --> 00:44:53.650
So what you will see here is
the Fourier transform of this.

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:55.260
[INAUDIBLE] before.

00:44:55.260 --> 00:44:58.510
It's these three spikes again.

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:03.580
The Fourier transform of
the three spikes is just a 1

00:45:03.580 --> 00:45:04.960
plus a cosine.

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:07.270
The relative strength of
these might change according

00:45:07.270 --> 00:45:11.160
to the properties of these--

00:45:11.160 --> 00:45:13.860
of the transmission of the mask.

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:20.740
But anyway, what you see finally
is an object which is like--

00:45:20.740 --> 00:45:28.210
you see the 1 plus cosine
type variation in amplitude.

00:45:28.210 --> 00:45:32.530
And so you notice that
this thing here started

00:45:32.530 --> 00:45:36.740
with these very square edges.

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:39.860
We no longer see the
very square edges.

00:45:39.860 --> 00:45:46.490
So this is an example of
how we've lost resolution.

00:45:46.490 --> 00:45:50.660
The optical system has got
a certain finite resolution.

00:45:50.660 --> 00:45:53.810
There's detail in
this original object

00:45:53.810 --> 00:45:56.720
that we can't actually
see in the final image.

00:45:56.720 --> 00:45:58.655
And this is because
not all the light

00:45:58.655 --> 00:45:59.780
has got through the system.

00:46:07.150 --> 00:46:12.010
OK, so we're going to look
at a particular case now.

00:46:12.010 --> 00:46:14.830
This is the bit I was saying
I wasn't very keen on.

00:46:14.830 --> 00:46:16.090
No, no, it's all right.

00:46:16.090 --> 00:46:18.520
But anyway, there's
a load of maths

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:22.360
here, which I might
actually gloss over a bit,

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:24.950
and let you look at
it yourself later.

00:46:24.950 --> 00:46:26.690
But basically,
then, we're looking

00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:29.890
at a particular example.

00:46:29.890 --> 00:46:34.855
It's a binary grating with
perfect contrast, m equals 1--

00:46:34.855 --> 00:46:36.700
i.e., this goes
from black to white.

00:46:36.700 --> 00:46:37.990
That's what that means.

00:46:37.990 --> 00:46:42.040
It's got a period of 10 microns.

00:46:42.040 --> 00:46:44.650
The spacing, the
period, is the distance

00:46:44.650 --> 00:46:48.550
between the repeat
on this grating.

00:46:48.550 --> 00:46:52.810
And it's got a duty
cycle of a third, which

00:46:52.810 --> 00:46:59.220
means that the white bit is
a third of the black bit.

00:46:59.220 --> 00:47:00.370
Is that what that means?

00:47:00.370 --> 00:47:00.850
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:00.850 --> 00:47:01.920
COLIN SHEPPARD: A
third of the whole.

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:02.795
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:02.795 --> 00:47:05.570
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah,
a third of the period.

00:47:05.570 --> 00:47:11.550
OK, and then we're also told
that the 4F system consists

00:47:11.550 --> 00:47:16.720
of two identical lenses of focal
length f equals 20 centimeters.

00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:20.040
So both f1 and f2
are 20 centimeters.

00:47:20.040 --> 00:47:23.760
And we put a pupil
mask of diameter

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:29.150
3 centimeters here
at the Fourier plane.

00:47:29.150 --> 00:47:33.467
What is the intensity observed
at the output image plane?

00:47:33.467 --> 00:47:34.425
So that's the question.

00:47:42.780 --> 00:47:46.890
OK, the secrets to solve this
kind of problem, what you've

00:47:46.890 --> 00:47:49.500
got to do is to
work out what you're

00:47:49.500 --> 00:47:52.230
going to get in this
plane, which is basically

00:47:52.230 --> 00:47:54.780
the Fourier transform of this.

00:47:54.780 --> 00:48:00.330
And then you're going to
have to multiply by the mask

00:48:00.330 --> 00:48:02.490
and see which of those
orders get through.

00:48:02.490 --> 00:48:07.920
So the relative scaling of this
diffraction pattern in the mask

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:10.380
is obviously all
important for that.

00:48:10.380 --> 00:48:12.870
If you don't get that
right, then you'll

00:48:12.870 --> 00:48:17.870
get the wrong answer,
obviously, because you

00:48:17.870 --> 00:48:19.870
might get orders getting
through that shouldn't,

00:48:19.870 --> 00:48:22.110
or the other way around.

00:48:22.110 --> 00:48:28.440
And so once we've done
that, we know now what

00:48:28.440 --> 00:48:34.720
the grating orders, the Fourier
components in the final image,

00:48:34.720 --> 00:48:35.840
are going to be.

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:38.400
And we then do another
Fourier transfer.

00:48:38.400 --> 00:48:39.960
And we've got the
image amplitude.

00:48:47.420 --> 00:48:48.640
There we are.

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:53.878
Again, we go [? do ?] scaling
to get it the right size.

00:48:53.878 --> 00:48:55.420
Normally, of course,
at the very end,

00:48:55.420 --> 00:48:57.920
we would be interested in
intensity, not amplitude,

00:48:57.920 --> 00:48:58.420
as well.

00:49:06.390 --> 00:49:09.720
OK, so this is our
example low-pass

00:49:09.720 --> 00:49:13.230
filtering, a binary
amplitude grating.

00:49:13.230 --> 00:49:17.040
So this is this grating
as we've chosen.

00:49:17.040 --> 00:49:22.980
And so you can see this, that
the dimension's in microns.

00:49:22.980 --> 00:49:27.820
So this is quite a fine grating.

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:30.930
So you can see that it's
not symmetrical, by the way.

00:49:30.930 --> 00:49:35.890
The duty cycle is
not a half, right?

00:49:35.890 --> 00:49:39.730
So the width of
the bright regions

00:49:39.730 --> 00:49:42.940
is smaller than the width
of the dark regions.

00:49:42.940 --> 00:49:44.380
And that's important
when it comes

00:49:44.380 --> 00:49:46.990
to looking at the
Fourier transform,

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:49.120
and therefore the
spectrum of that.

00:49:49.120 --> 00:49:53.430
And then the pupil
mask that we're

00:49:53.430 --> 00:49:56.020
going to look at looks
something like that.

00:49:56.020 --> 00:49:59.860
We let through the
frequencies near the center.

00:49:59.860 --> 00:50:02.770
And we keep out--

00:50:02.770 --> 00:50:06.090
reject the frequencies which
are further from the center.

00:50:12.370 --> 00:50:17.820
OK, so for the Fourier
transformer of that,

00:50:17.820 --> 00:50:19.590
this is a repetitive function.

00:50:19.590 --> 00:50:23.670
So the Fourier transform just
becomes a Fourier series.

00:50:23.670 --> 00:50:28.930
And this is an expression for
the Fourier series of this.

00:50:28.930 --> 00:50:34.490
It basically consists
of two parts.

00:50:34.490 --> 00:50:39.070
It's got a sort of
envelope, which is a sinc.

00:50:39.070 --> 00:50:44.720
Basically, this is going to
consist of an infinite number

00:50:44.720 --> 00:50:48.910
of discrete frequencies.

00:50:48.910 --> 00:50:52.420
It's going to consist of
a constant term, which

00:50:52.420 --> 00:50:53.110
is the zero.

00:50:53.110 --> 00:50:58.860
It is going to consist of
a first harmonic and then

00:50:58.860 --> 00:51:02.590
a second harmonic and a
third harmonic, and so on.

00:51:02.590 --> 00:51:04.840
If the duty cycle
has been chosen

00:51:04.840 --> 00:51:09.820
to be a half, i.e. it was a
square wave, then by symmetry,

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:11.740
it turns out that
the second harmonic

00:51:11.740 --> 00:51:15.160
and the fourth harmonic
and all those all vanish.

00:51:15.160 --> 00:51:18.520
So you'd only end up with the
zero, the first, the third,

00:51:18.520 --> 00:51:21.140
the fifth, and so on.

00:51:21.140 --> 00:51:25.540
But in general, there will
be all the orders there.

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:29.230
And the relative
strength of those orders

00:51:29.230 --> 00:51:35.470
here, you can see the
size depends on the value

00:51:35.470 --> 00:51:37.360
of this sinc function.

00:51:37.360 --> 00:51:41.630
Actually, that's a very easy way
of seeing about the even orders

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:42.940
canceling.

00:51:42.940 --> 00:51:48.640
Because what happens is, if
the duty factor is a half,

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:52.960
it turns out that
the even orders when

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:57.550
q equals even number
coincide with the zeros

00:51:57.550 --> 00:51:58.750
of the sinc function.

00:51:58.750 --> 00:52:01.720
And that's why they vanish.

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:09.240
So where this comes
from is that--

00:52:09.240 --> 00:52:13.260
so we're saying that
this function is a--

00:52:16.350 --> 00:52:20.060
maybe it's easier if I go on
to the next slide, I think,

00:52:20.060 --> 00:52:21.610
which is the Fourier transform.

00:52:21.610 --> 00:52:26.570
Yeah, so the Fourier
transform, the strength

00:52:26.570 --> 00:52:30.510
of these components is
what we've got to find out.

00:52:30.510 --> 00:52:34.700
And so this function
Fourier transforms

00:52:34.700 --> 00:52:38.720
to something which is a
series of delta functions

00:52:38.720 --> 00:52:42.860
corresponding to the different
orders, different values, of q.

00:52:42.860 --> 00:52:46.670
And the strength of the
different components

00:52:46.670 --> 00:52:48.380
is given by the
value of the sync.

