01:02:24.870 --> 01:02:28.920
that it was a this
rectangular grating.

01:02:31.900 --> 01:02:36.550
Yeah, and finally, though,
as I just mentioned briefly

01:02:36.550 --> 01:02:38.230
a little while ago,
what you actually

01:02:38.230 --> 01:02:39.910
see is not the amplitude.

01:02:39.910 --> 01:02:43.030
What you see is the
intensity, which

01:02:43.030 --> 01:02:46.160
is the modulus square
of the amplitude.

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:50.410
So you remember, we
said that we normally

01:02:50.410 --> 01:02:53.170
are going to call the intensity
just the modulus square

01:02:53.170 --> 01:02:54.380
of the amplitude.

01:02:54.380 --> 01:02:57.400
There perhaps should be
some halves and funny things

01:02:57.400 --> 01:02:59.920
out there if we were
really doing it according

01:02:59.920 --> 01:03:03.520
to the Poynting vector.

01:03:03.520 --> 01:03:05.770
But normally, we don't
bother with that.

01:03:05.770 --> 01:03:08.150
We just say it's
the modulus square.

01:03:08.150 --> 01:03:11.170
So the modulus
square of this, we're

01:03:11.170 --> 01:03:17.050
going to get this squared and
twice the product of these two,

01:03:17.050 --> 01:03:18.580
and then this one squared.

01:03:18.580 --> 01:03:22.190
So we get this term
in Cos squared.

01:03:22.190 --> 01:03:26.570
And then you have to remember
your formulae that you learn

01:03:26.570 --> 01:03:33.060
in maths, Cos 2 theta equals 1
minus 2 cosine squared theta,

01:03:33.060 --> 01:03:35.390
which allows us the right
Cos squared theta is

01:03:35.390 --> 01:03:38.120
1 plus Cos theta over 2.

01:03:38.120 --> 01:03:45.370
So this Cos squared, we can
now replace by a constant plus

01:03:45.370 --> 01:03:48.320
a cosine of twice the angle.

01:03:48.320 --> 01:03:53.090
And so this is the
constant bit, and this is

01:03:53.090 --> 01:03:56.390
the cosine of twice the angle.

01:03:56.390 --> 01:04:01.210
All right, so that gives a
another harmonic in the image.

01:04:01.210 --> 01:04:03.770
So that's something that
people are a bit confused

01:04:03.770 --> 01:04:05.690
by sometimes, first of all.

01:04:05.690 --> 01:04:08.000
Because we've gone
through a lot of talk

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:11.420
about how it's only the first
time on it that's gone through.

01:04:11.420 --> 01:04:14.990
But actually now, when
we look at the intensity,

01:04:14.990 --> 01:04:17.600
we've now got a second
harmonic that's appearing

01:04:17.600 --> 01:04:20.280
in the final intensity.

01:04:20.280 --> 01:04:23.130
So note, the second
harmonic term intensity

01:04:23.130 --> 01:04:26.800
due to the magnitude
square operation.

01:04:26.800 --> 01:04:30.640
This term explains the ringing
in coherent low-pass filtering

01:04:30.640 --> 01:04:32.230
systems.

01:04:32.230 --> 01:04:45.660
So the ringing is the wiggles
you get on the sharp edge.

01:04:45.660 --> 01:04:48.800
Right, and that's a sketch
of what it looks like.

01:04:48.800 --> 01:04:52.990
So it doesn't look quite
like a cosine grating

01:04:52.990 --> 01:04:57.100
anymore, because
when you square it,

01:04:57.100 --> 01:05:02.170
the low values get depressed
more than the high values.

01:05:02.170 --> 01:05:06.030
So it makes it look
more peaky, like that.

