01:22:40.920 --> 01:22:42.380
And that's neat.

01:22:42.380 --> 01:22:43.130
Very interesting.

01:22:43.130 --> 01:22:44.010
AUDIENCE: But with
different amplitudes.

01:22:44.010 --> 01:22:46.135
COLIN SHEPPARD: But with
different amplitudes given

01:22:46.135 --> 01:22:47.690
by these two strengths here.

01:22:51.950 --> 01:23:00.690
And then-- yeah, so then we
have to put the values of u

01:23:00.690 --> 01:23:02.580
in terms of the x.

01:23:02.580 --> 01:23:04.860
And then we combine
the two exponentials.

01:23:04.860 --> 01:23:06.060
Well, can't do that anymore.

01:23:06.060 --> 01:23:06.640
Can we?

01:23:06.640 --> 01:23:08.290
Oh yes, we can.

01:23:08.290 --> 01:23:12.250
AUDIENCE: Well, you can,
but [INAUDIBLE] sine and the

01:23:12.250 --> 01:23:14.230
cosine.

01:23:14.230 --> 01:23:16.230
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah, exactly.

01:23:16.230 --> 01:23:18.470
So have you actually
done that, then?

01:23:18.470 --> 01:23:20.770
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:23:20.770 --> 01:23:23.330
COLIN SHEPPARD: Right,
so you've got to do

01:23:23.330 --> 01:23:25.553
