01:24:47.640 --> 01:24:51.670
Right, another example--
a new pupil mask

01:24:51.670 --> 01:24:56.200
consisting of two holes,
each of diameter 1 centimeter

01:24:56.200 --> 01:24:59.980
and centered further away
from the axis plus or minus

01:24:59.980 --> 01:25:04.070
2 centimeters from the
optical axis respectively.

01:25:04.070 --> 01:25:08.350
What is the intensity observed
at the output image plane?

01:25:08.350 --> 01:25:11.320
Right, so at least it's
told us the 2 centimeters.

01:25:11.320 --> 01:25:12.880
We know where that is.

01:25:12.880 --> 01:25:15.100
We don't have to worry
about working out

01:25:15.100 --> 01:25:20.380
what 0.3479 degrees is.

01:25:20.380 --> 01:25:24.880
We know that the first
order was at 1 centimeter.

01:25:24.880 --> 01:25:30.310
So the second order is
where the aperture is.

01:25:30.310 --> 01:25:32.520
So the second order is
going to get through,

01:25:32.520 --> 01:25:34.940
the plus 2 and the minus 2.

01:25:40.590 --> 01:25:44.940
And did not appear,
then, up there?

01:25:44.940 --> 01:25:48.540
Right, so the second harmonic
is going to get through.

01:25:48.540 --> 01:25:50.443
And when you do
the square of that,

01:25:50.443 --> 01:25:52.110
you're going to get
the fourth harmonic.

01:25:55.090 --> 01:25:58.610
So this is going through
the mass of that, then.

01:25:58.610 --> 01:26:02.090
So we've got just
these two components.

01:26:04.850 --> 01:26:06.730
So these have now
got 2 centimeters

01:26:06.730 --> 01:26:09.460
in, rather than 1 centimeter.

01:26:09.460 --> 01:26:14.050
So that means that you
get a 2 multiplied in here

01:26:14.050 --> 01:26:16.160
that wasn't there before.

01:26:16.160 --> 01:26:21.300
So that's where the
second harmonic comes in.

01:26:21.300 --> 01:26:23.820
And then when you do the
square, again, you're

01:26:23.820 --> 01:26:26.700
only going to get the
cosine and no constants.

01:26:26.700 --> 01:26:31.500
And then you do Cos squared and
change that into double angles,

01:26:31.500 --> 01:26:34.530
or fourth angles, actually.

01:26:34.530 --> 01:26:37.350
And now we're going to
see what it looks like.

01:26:37.350 --> 01:26:42.490
And now, it's even worse
an image of what we wanted.

01:26:42.490 --> 01:26:45.920
So I guess this is maybe
telling us what we shouldn't do,

01:26:45.920 --> 01:26:47.220
rather than what we should do.

01:26:47.220 --> 01:26:48.610
AUDIENCE: Got another question.

01:26:48.610 --> 01:26:51.010
Is this is still
assuming f1 equals f2?

01:26:51.010 --> 01:26:54.722
And what happens if
f2 is smaller than f1?

01:26:54.722 --> 01:26:56.680
COLIN SHEPPARD: All it
would do, if you changed

01:26:56.680 --> 01:27:02.140
the relative values of an
f1 an f2, all it would do

01:27:02.140 --> 01:27:06.790
is change the size
of the final image.

01:27:06.790 --> 01:27:09.760
If you think about this system--

01:27:09.760 --> 01:27:13.280
let's go back to one where
it shows that-- there we are.

01:27:13.280 --> 01:27:25.060
You can see that the relative
distances from the axis only

01:27:25.060 --> 01:27:28.240
depend on this part
of the optical system.

01:27:28.240 --> 01:27:32.410
And then after the
pupil mask, we've

01:27:32.410 --> 01:27:34.570
already decided,
then, what orders

01:27:34.570 --> 01:27:36.820
get into the final image.

01:27:36.820 --> 01:27:39.370
And then the final part,
all that's going to do

01:27:39.370 --> 01:27:43.150
is just change the relative
size of the final image you see.

01:27:57.080 --> 01:27:59.510
Right, now we're going to do
another bit more complicated

01:27:59.510 --> 01:28:00.100
one--

01:28:00.100 --> 01:28:02.750
a phase pupil mask.

01:28:02.750 --> 01:28:07.070
And so what this
is shown as is, you

01:28:07.070 --> 01:28:11.300
can see it's got an opaque
part of the screen here.

01:28:11.300 --> 01:28:14.690
And then in the
central part, it's

01:28:14.690 --> 01:28:21.560
transparent, but it's got
some sort of structure there--

01:28:21.560 --> 01:28:25.160
some diffractive
dielectric element,

01:28:25.160 --> 01:28:31.160
which changes the relative
phase of this order compared

01:28:31.160 --> 01:28:34.180
with the other orders.

01:28:34.180 --> 01:28:39.060
So the question is, what's
that going to do to your image?

01:28:39.060 --> 01:28:41.430
So the rest of the system
is completely the same.

01:28:44.860 --> 01:28:48.517
So this is what we are
considering putting in there.

01:28:48.517 --> 01:28:50.350
It doesn't matter what
the thickness of this

01:28:50.350 --> 01:28:53.590
is, because all
that's going to do

01:28:53.590 --> 01:28:57.040
is change the relative
phase of all of these.

01:28:57.040 --> 01:28:59.638
So it won't affect how
they interfere with each.

01:28:59.638 --> 01:29:01.930
It will just change the phase
of the final image, which

01:29:01.930 --> 01:29:03.580
you don't see anyway.

01:29:03.580 --> 01:29:08.080
But what is important
is this bit here.

01:29:08.080 --> 01:29:14.530
The thickness of this
s equals 0.25 microns,

01:29:14.530 --> 01:29:20.680
and the wavelength was
half of 0.5 microns.

01:29:20.680 --> 01:29:23.470
So that's lambda by 2.

01:29:23.470 --> 01:29:29.210
So that means it changes
the phase by 180 degrees.

01:29:29.210 --> 01:29:32.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:29:32.110 --> 01:29:33.661
COLIN SHEPPARD: Ah, n minus 1.

01:29:33.661 --> 01:29:35.870
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
the next slide.

01:29:35.870 --> 01:29:37.465
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah, n minus 1.

01:29:37.465 --> 01:29:39.478
So it's not going to do that.

01:29:39.478 --> 01:29:40.020
Take it back.

01:29:40.020 --> 01:29:42.054
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:29:42.054 --> 01:29:44.600
COLIN SHEPPARD:
It's [INAUDIBLE]..

01:29:44.600 --> 01:29:51.770
OK, this is known as a phase
pupil mask or a pupil phase

01:29:51.770 --> 01:29:54.285
mask, or a mask pupil phase.

01:29:56.840 --> 01:29:59.140
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:29:59.140 --> 01:30:01.060
COLIN SHEPPARD:
Yeah, that's right.

01:30:01.060 --> 01:30:02.740
So that must be in
the next lecture,

01:30:02.740 --> 01:30:04.640
because it's not in this one.

01:30:04.640 --> 01:30:06.640
So let's get down to
the real application.

01:30:06.640 --> 01:30:11.560
OK, so George said that I
would have just failed the exam

01:30:11.560 --> 01:30:15.250
because I forgot the minus 1.

01:30:15.250 --> 01:30:19.000
Of course, this light
goes through the glass.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:22.660
But this light goes through
the glass and then the air.

01:30:22.660 --> 01:30:26.110
So to work out the
relative phases of these,

01:30:26.110 --> 01:30:31.000
you have to look at the relative
change in the refractive index

01:30:31.000 --> 01:30:33.010
times the optical thickness.

01:30:33.010 --> 01:30:41.620
So this is 0.25 microns,
and this is at 0.25 microns

01:30:41.620 --> 01:30:43.420
divided by the wavelength.

01:30:43.420 --> 01:30:48.295
And it's going to be
multiplied by 1.5 minus 1.

01:30:48.295 --> 01:30:50.860
So this is assuming it's glass.

01:30:50.860 --> 01:30:57.390
So this means that the
phase change is pi over 2.

01:30:57.390 --> 01:31:00.400
So not pi, but pi over 2.

01:31:05.700 --> 01:31:08.438
OK, so exactly the same grating.

01:31:08.438 --> 01:31:09.480
These are all the orders.

01:31:12.480 --> 01:31:18.210
And so you see, first of all,
we get rid of these outer ones.

01:31:18.210 --> 01:31:20.790
We let through just these three.

01:31:20.790 --> 01:31:25.410
But of those, we're
also going to change

01:31:25.410 --> 01:31:30.360
the relative phase of this one
relative to the other, too.

01:31:30.360 --> 01:31:33.900
That doesn't matter, of
course, in your sum whether you

01:31:33.900 --> 01:31:35.970
change the phase of
this or you change

01:31:35.970 --> 01:31:37.230
the phase of the other two.

01:31:37.230 --> 01:31:40.770
Certainly, the relative phase,
which is the important thing.

01:31:50.740 --> 01:31:53.070
OK, so these are the
three conditions, then.

01:31:53.070 --> 01:31:56.410
For the ones that are not
don't get through at all,

01:31:56.410 --> 01:31:58.420
the strength of those is zero.

01:31:58.420 --> 01:32:05.150
Then here, we're taking these
ones to be of strength one,

01:32:05.150 --> 01:32:11.630
and this one in the center to
be strength of e to the i phi.

01:32:11.630 --> 01:32:16.790
And we know that
phi is pi over 2.

01:32:16.790 --> 01:32:21.520
So this is e to the i pi
over 2, which is just i.

01:32:21.520 --> 01:32:23.840
Is that right?

01:32:23.840 --> 01:32:27.310
Why have we got this i
minus 1 then, George?

01:32:27.310 --> 01:32:32.380
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
[INAUDIBLE] So one way

01:32:32.380 --> 01:32:36.970
to write this pupil function
is as a rect that is as big

01:32:36.970 --> 01:32:37.765
as the opening.

01:32:37.765 --> 01:32:39.790
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah, OK.

01:32:39.790 --> 01:32:41.800
Sorry, yeah.

01:32:41.800 --> 01:32:51.280
So you can think of this as
being the whole thing minus--

01:32:51.280 --> 01:32:54.900
well, this on top of
the whole rectangle.

01:32:54.900 --> 01:32:58.660
Otherwise, you'd have to do this
little rectangle and this bit

01:32:58.660 --> 01:33:02.120
a rectangle and this bit of
rectangle as three things.

01:33:02.120 --> 01:33:05.050
So you could do it either
of those ways, I guess.

01:33:05.050 --> 01:33:07.810
But the way that George
has done it here,

01:33:07.810 --> 01:33:10.060
it's the rectangle, of
the whole [? lot, ?]

01:33:10.060 --> 01:33:14.410
it's all of this
minus the central one,

01:33:14.410 --> 01:33:17.140
plus the central one
with the phase change.

01:33:17.140 --> 01:33:19.450
So that's the minus
the one that's

01:33:19.450 --> 01:33:24.740
not there plus the one that is
there where the phase changed.

01:33:24.740 --> 01:33:27.820
And yeah, so now--

01:33:27.820 --> 01:33:32.060
well of course, we still get
all these delta functions.

01:33:32.060 --> 01:33:35.600
But now we've got
some i's coming in.

01:33:35.600 --> 01:33:36.100
Sorry?

01:33:36.100 --> 01:33:36.975
AUDIENCE: Just one i.

01:33:36.975 --> 01:33:39.850
COLIN SHEPPARD:
Just one i, yeah.

01:33:39.850 --> 01:33:47.120
And then these two combine
to produce cosine still.

01:33:47.120 --> 01:33:50.160
I guess if you change the phase
of one relative to the other,

01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:51.900
it'd be more complicated.

01:33:51.900 --> 01:33:55.080
But these two produce a cosine.

01:33:55.080 --> 01:33:58.110
So we've got an i plus a cosine.

01:33:58.110 --> 01:34:00.980
And then we do the
modulus square of that.

01:34:00.980 --> 01:34:03.210
And the modulus square
of that, of course,

01:34:03.210 --> 01:34:06.590
is you're not going to get a
cross product term are you,

01:34:06.590 --> 01:34:10.860
because these two are
in phase quadrature.

01:34:10.860 --> 01:34:14.527
So when you do the modulus
square, you're only going--

01:34:14.527 --> 01:34:15.110
is that right?

01:34:15.110 --> 01:34:15.610
Yeah.

01:34:15.610 --> 01:34:17.800
You're going to get this
squared plus this squared.

01:34:17.800 --> 01:34:22.590
And this squared, you can
write as these two terms

01:34:22.590 --> 01:34:26.090
when you do the double angle.

01:34:26.090 --> 01:34:27.670
And I guess the next
one, we're going

01:34:27.670 --> 01:34:29.390
to see what it looks like.

01:34:29.390 --> 01:34:32.660
Ta-da, this is
what it looks like.

01:34:32.660 --> 01:34:36.650
First harmonic in field,
second harmonic in intensity

01:34:36.650 --> 01:34:38.780
because of the squaring.

01:34:38.780 --> 01:34:42.950
And again, the contrast is
now much reduced, actually,

01:34:42.950 --> 01:34:44.930
in this case--

01:34:44.930 --> 01:34:48.160
down to 0.25.

01:34:48.160 --> 01:34:51.455
So I guess this hasn't turned
out to be a very [INAUDIBLE]

01:34:51.455 --> 01:34:52.540
strategy.

01:34:52.540 --> 01:34:55.030
This lecture seems to
be mainly showing you

01:34:55.030 --> 01:34:57.500
what you shouldn't do when
you make your microscope.

01:34:57.500 --> 01:34:59.263
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:34:59.263 --> 01:35:00.706
COLIN SHEPPARD: [LAUGHS]

01:35:00.706 --> 01:35:03.592
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:35:03.592 --> 01:35:09.590
COLIN SHEPPARD: OK,
so now we're going

01:35:09.590 --> 01:35:11.840
to go on to think
of this in terms

01:35:11.840 --> 01:35:14.660
of what we call a
point spread function

01:35:14.660 --> 01:35:16.490
of the low-pass filter.

01:35:16.490 --> 01:35:19.400
So do you remember, going
back to our analogies

01:35:19.400 --> 01:35:24.740
with electronics, we can
think of-- any electronics you

01:35:24.740 --> 01:35:30.140
can either think of
your hi-fi amplifier

01:35:30.140 --> 01:35:32.610
as being like a
black box, don't you?

01:35:32.610 --> 01:35:37.090
And you put in something
and you get out something.

01:35:37.090 --> 01:35:39.690
And you can either
think of what happens

01:35:39.690 --> 01:35:45.040
was inside there as being like
an h of t, an impulse response.

01:35:45.040 --> 01:35:50.770
Or you can think of it as
being a frequency response.

01:35:50.770 --> 01:35:54.670
So there are two
different ways of thinking

01:35:54.670 --> 01:35:56.020
about this black box.

01:35:56.020 --> 01:35:58.240
The same is true in this case.

01:35:58.240 --> 01:36:00.040
So up until now,
we've been thinking

01:36:00.040 --> 01:36:04.420
of this in terms of the
frequency response, what

01:36:04.420 --> 01:36:06.990
frequencies get into the image.

01:36:06.990 --> 01:36:09.370
And now we're going to think
of what that means in terms

01:36:09.370 --> 01:36:11.055
of the point spread function.

01:36:11.055 --> 01:36:13.180
We've come across the point
spread function before,

01:36:13.180 --> 01:36:14.890
of course.

01:36:14.890 --> 01:36:20.820
So the point spread
function is basically

01:36:20.820 --> 01:36:24.660
the image of a point object.

01:36:24.660 --> 01:36:27.780
And our point objects, we
make by having a screen

01:36:27.780 --> 01:36:30.300
with a very small hole in.

01:36:30.300 --> 01:36:32.445
So this, then, is
going to expand.

01:36:36.220 --> 01:36:38.200
It reached the lens.

01:36:38.200 --> 01:36:40.310
It's going to be
collimated because we

01:36:40.310 --> 01:36:43.180
were seeing this on the axis.

01:36:43.180 --> 01:36:50.210
This collimated beam is going
to arrive at our pupil mask.

01:36:50.210 --> 01:36:51.890
Part of this collimated
beam is going

01:36:51.890 --> 01:36:53.500
to go through the aperture.

01:36:53.500 --> 01:36:55.700
It's going to get to a lens.

01:36:55.700 --> 01:36:58.420
It's then going
to be focused down

01:36:58.420 --> 01:37:06.540
and produce a converging wave
to form a spot on the screen.

01:37:06.540 --> 01:37:09.110
So this is what we think of as--

01:37:09.110 --> 01:37:12.230
the final spot is going to be
what we call the point spread

01:37:12.230 --> 01:37:14.947
function h of x, y.

01:37:18.930 --> 01:37:24.610
OK, so how do we work out
this point spread function?

01:37:24.610 --> 01:37:28.440
So what we do is, we can
again work through this system

01:37:28.440 --> 01:37:30.450
in terms of Fourier transforms.

01:37:30.450 --> 01:37:32.590
This is a delta function.

01:37:32.590 --> 01:37:35.160
So the Fourier transform
of a delta function

01:37:35.160 --> 01:37:37.020
is just a constant.

01:37:37.020 --> 01:37:42.600
We multiply the constant
by the pupil mask.

01:37:42.600 --> 01:37:47.080
And then we've got
another system here,

01:37:47.080 --> 01:37:50.070
which does another
Fourier transform.

01:37:50.070 --> 01:37:54.930
So what we're going to get
in the final plane, the image

01:37:54.930 --> 01:37:57.390
of a point object, is
going to be the Fourier

01:37:57.390 --> 01:37:59.235
transform of the pupil mask.

01:38:02.070 --> 01:38:04.710
And yeah, so it
makes the point here

01:38:04.710 --> 01:38:08.520
that we have to be careful, of
course, how we scale things.

01:38:08.520 --> 01:38:10.980
And of course, the
scaling is going

01:38:10.980 --> 01:38:14.898
to depend on the relative
sizes of these f1 and f2

01:38:14.898 --> 01:38:15.690
as well, of course.

01:38:21.150 --> 01:38:25.620
So, example-- if we got
the low pass filter,

01:38:25.620 --> 01:38:27.630
so 0 is in the center.

01:38:27.630 --> 01:38:29.940
It lets through the
low frequencies,

01:38:29.940 --> 01:38:33.450
stops the outer frequencies.

01:38:33.450 --> 01:38:37.740
So this is the pupil mask.

01:38:37.740 --> 01:38:43.490
What does the point spread
function of that give?

01:38:43.490 --> 01:38:51.530
And so we're assuming that
the input transparency

01:38:51.530 --> 01:38:54.540
is delta x on the axis.

01:38:54.540 --> 01:38:57.460
So this is illuminated on-axis.

01:38:57.460 --> 01:39:02.920
The field after the pupil
mask is just the same

01:39:02.920 --> 01:39:05.670
as the pupil mask.

01:39:05.670 --> 01:39:08.480
And then we Fourier
transform that,

01:39:08.480 --> 01:39:11.240
and it's going to give a sinc.

01:39:11.240 --> 01:39:14.800
That the Fourier
transform of rect is sinc.

01:39:14.800 --> 01:39:18.650
And here, we've got the
relative sizes of this

01:39:18.650 --> 01:39:21.590
as well, so that we
know how big it is.

01:39:24.710 --> 01:39:29.000
And so that the amplitude
point spread function, then,

01:39:29.000 --> 01:39:36.000
is this Fourier transform
rescaled with this x dashed

01:39:36.000 --> 01:39:36.960
over lambda f.

01:39:36.960 --> 01:39:41.280
We replace the u by the
x [INAUDIBLE] lambda f.

01:39:41.280 --> 01:39:44.010
And this finally,
then, is our answer.

01:40:02.980 --> 01:40:05.720
Which three times
is it saying there?

01:40:05.720 --> 01:40:07.437
This three, or is that three?

01:40:07.437 --> 01:40:08.520
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah.

01:40:08.520 --> 01:40:12.300
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah,
OK, because the energy

01:40:12.300 --> 01:40:14.310
has to be conserved
by this thing.

01:40:14.310 --> 01:40:16.780
So you remember,
there's this theorem

01:40:16.780 --> 01:40:18.840
in Fourier transforms
again that says

01:40:18.840 --> 01:40:22.560
the area under the
function squared

01:40:22.560 --> 01:40:26.870
is equal to the area under
the Fourier transform squared.

01:40:26.870 --> 01:40:30.470
So it's conservation of energy.

01:40:30.470 --> 01:40:36.670
And so this is the amplitude
point spread function.

01:40:36.670 --> 01:40:40.450
It's sinc, so it goes negative.

01:40:40.450 --> 01:40:43.300
Sinc is sine pi x over pi x.

01:40:43.300 --> 01:40:44.900
So it goes negative.

01:40:44.900 --> 01:40:46.400
So that's why it's plotted here.

01:40:46.400 --> 01:40:49.140
This is 0.

01:40:49.140 --> 01:40:58.760
It wiggles up and down
above the 0 [? light. ?]

01:40:58.760 --> 01:41:04.100
And so of course, if you looked
at the image of a point object,

01:41:04.100 --> 01:41:07.400
you'd see the modulus
square of this.

01:41:07.400 --> 01:41:12.550
Just like when we looked at
our examples of the grating,

01:41:12.550 --> 01:41:15.860
we finally look at the
actual intensity, rather than

01:41:15.860 --> 01:41:16.910
the amplitude.

01:41:16.910 --> 01:41:19.590
The intensity, of course,
is always positive.

01:41:19.590 --> 01:41:22.010
So you'd actually be looking
at the square of that.

01:41:22.010 --> 01:41:26.380
But if you're trying to think
of this thing as being--

01:41:26.380 --> 01:41:28.670
what we're going to carry
on to say, of course,

01:41:28.670 --> 01:41:33.080
is in Fourier space,
or in Fourier domain,

01:41:33.080 --> 01:41:35.830
the spatial frequencies
of the object

01:41:35.830 --> 01:41:39.340
are multiplied by the mask.

01:41:39.340 --> 01:41:47.570
In terms of real space, you're
going to get a convolution.

01:41:47.570 --> 01:41:49.680
The product becomes
a convolution.

01:41:49.680 --> 01:41:54.230
So we're going to convolve our
objects with an amplitude point

01:41:54.230 --> 01:41:56.083
spread function.

01:41:56.083 --> 01:41:58.250
But we have to do it with
the amplitude point spread

01:41:58.250 --> 01:42:01.100
function, find the final
the total amplitude

01:42:01.100 --> 01:42:04.460
in the image, and then
the modulus square

01:42:04.460 --> 01:42:08.210
to find the final the intensity.

01:42:08.210 --> 01:42:11.090
OK, and this is an example
of the point spread

01:42:11.090 --> 01:42:14.960
function of this phase
filter we looked at.

01:42:14.960 --> 01:42:19.610
The pupil mask, this is
the same as we had before.

01:42:19.610 --> 01:42:21.020
So this is its modulus.

01:42:21.020 --> 01:42:23.280
This is the phase.

01:42:23.280 --> 01:42:27.980
And if you calculate the
point spread function of this,

01:42:27.980 --> 01:42:28.745
it comes to this.

01:42:28.745 --> 01:42:30.080
This is the modulus.

01:42:30.080 --> 01:42:32.090
This is the phase.

01:42:32.090 --> 01:42:35.810
So you can see that that is why
we got a pretty horrible image.

01:42:35.810 --> 01:42:39.530
It's because it's got a very
nasty point spread function.

01:42:39.530 --> 01:42:41.870
[INAUDIBLE] point spread
function, for a start,

01:42:41.870 --> 01:42:44.460
it's got these very
large side lobes,

01:42:44.460 --> 01:42:46.145
which normally we don't like.

01:42:46.145 --> 01:42:49.070
We normally like to have
our point spread function

01:42:49.070 --> 01:42:54.110
to be nicely narrow and smooth,
and without the big side lobes.

01:42:54.110 --> 01:42:55.610
And then more than
that, it's also

01:42:55.610 --> 01:42:59.015
got these horrible phase
jumps, which I think

01:42:59.015 --> 01:43:02.780
are very likely to produce
a pretty awful image, which

01:43:02.780 --> 01:43:04.890
is probably what we saw.

01:43:04.890 --> 01:43:08.010
So this goes through the
sum of actually doing that.

01:43:08.010 --> 01:43:11.100
So this is the same as
we had before, then--

01:43:11.100 --> 01:43:13.370
the big rectangle minus
the little rectangle

01:43:13.370 --> 01:43:15.140
with the phase.

01:43:15.140 --> 01:43:20.070
And then we've got to do the
Fourier transform of that.

01:43:20.070 --> 01:43:22.850
And so the way we've
done it here, then,

01:43:22.850 --> 01:43:25.940
we just got the sum
of two rectangles.

01:43:25.940 --> 01:43:28.490
Each of them becomes a sinc.

01:43:28.490 --> 01:43:32.960
But you've got this i here
you have to be careful of.

01:43:32.960 --> 01:43:38.510
And then finally, we work
out the modulus square

01:43:38.510 --> 01:43:41.570
of the part of the
point spread function

01:43:41.570 --> 01:43:44.780
and the phase of the point
spread function right so

01:43:44.780 --> 01:43:48.590
this is the modulus square
of the point spread function.

01:43:48.590 --> 01:43:51.170
So these side lobes are
actually quite huge--

01:43:54.220 --> 01:43:55.120
quite big.

01:44:03.530 --> 01:44:06.470
OK, yeah, that's just looking at
the difference between the two,

01:44:06.470 --> 01:44:07.640
then.

01:44:07.640 --> 01:44:12.690
So if we have our
low-pass filter--

01:44:12.690 --> 01:44:15.650
so this is what I was saying
about these being huge.

01:44:15.650 --> 01:44:20.380
You see the low-pass
filter, these side lobes

01:44:20.380 --> 01:44:22.490
are pretty small by comparison.

01:44:22.490 --> 01:44:28.160
I guess you could use some sort
of shaded aperture, or maybe

01:44:28.160 --> 01:44:31.670
an aperture with some structure
that would allow you to make

01:44:31.670 --> 01:44:35.870
those side lobes even smaller.

01:44:35.870 --> 01:44:40.300
This is this process that's
sometimes called apodization.

01:44:40.300 --> 01:44:44.410
Apodization means
to cut off the feet.

01:44:44.410 --> 01:44:47.150
I think if George
was giving the talk,

01:44:47.150 --> 01:44:49.100
he'd say something
about the Greek

01:44:49.100 --> 01:44:52.840
for feet being something
to do with pod.

01:44:52.840 --> 01:44:53.710
Right, there we are.

